{"parse":{"title":"Cross-serial dependencies","pageid":40530379,"revid":828435312,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><div class=\"thumb tright\"><div class=\"thumbinner\" style=\"width:402px;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Schematic_of_cross-serial_dependency.png\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"A diagram showing cross-serial dependency using lines and colors to represent the dependent pairs.\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/62/Schematic_of_cross-serial_dependency.png/400px-Schematic_of_cross-serial_dependency.png\" width=\"400\" height=\"104\" class=\"thumbimage\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/62/Schematic_of_cross-serial_dependency.png/600px-Schematic_of_cross-serial_dependency.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/62/Schematic_of_cross-serial_dependency.png/800px-Schematic_of_cross-serial_dependency.png 2x\" data-file-width=\"1498\" data-file-height=\"390\" /></a>  <div class=\"thumbcaption\"><div class=\"magnify\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Schematic_of_cross-serial_dependency.png\" class=\"internal\" title=\"Enlarge\"></a></div>A schematic showing cross-serial dependencies. Notice that the w's and v's, which represent words, each form respective series. Notice also that the lines representing the dependency relations mutually overlap.</div></div></div>\n<p>In <a href=\"/wiki/Linguistics\" title=\"Linguistics\">linguistics</a>, <b>cross-serial dependencies</b> (also called <b>crossing dependencies</b> by some authors<sup id=\"cite_ref-stabler2004_1-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-stabler2004-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup>) occur when the lines representing the <a href=\"/wiki/Dependency_grammar#What_dependencies_are\" title=\"Dependency grammar\">dependency relations</a> between two series of words cross over each other.<sup id=\"cite_ref-jurafsky2000_2-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-jurafsky2000-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> They are of particular interest to linguists who wish to determine the syntactic structure of natural language; languages containing an arbitrary number of them are non-context-free. By this fact, <a href=\"/wiki/Dutch_language\" title=\"Dutch language\">Dutch</a><sup id=\"cite_ref-bresnan1982_3-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-bresnan1982-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup> and <a href=\"/wiki/Swiss_German\" title=\"Swiss German\">Swiss-German</a><sup id=\"cite_ref-shieber1985_4-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-shieber1985-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup> have been proved to be non-context-free.\n</p>\n<div id=\"toc\" class=\"toc\"><input type=\"checkbox\" role=\"button\" id=\"toctogglecheckbox\" class=\"toctogglecheckbox\" style=\"display:none\" /><div class=\"toctitle\" lang=\"en\" dir=\"ltr\"><h2>Contents</h2><span class=\"toctogglespan\"><label class=\"toctogglelabel\" for=\"toctogglecheckbox\"></label></span></div>\n<ul>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-1\"><a href=\"#Example\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">1</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Example</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-2\"><a href=\"#Why_languages_containing_cross-serial_dependencies_are_non-context-free\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">2</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Why languages containing cross-serial dependencies are non-context-free</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-3\"><a href=\"#Treatment\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">3</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Treatment</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-4\"><a href=\"#References\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">4</span> <span class=\"toctext\">References</span></a></li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Example\">Example</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Cross-serial_dependencies&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: Example\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<style data-mw-deduplicate=\"TemplateStyles:r856303569\">@media all and (max-width:720px){.mw-parser-output .tmulti>.thumbinner{width:100%!important;max-width:none!important}.mw-parser-output .tmulti .tsingle{float:none!important;max-width:none!important;width:100%!important;text-align:center}}</style><div class=\"thumb tmulti tright\"><div class=\"thumbinner\" style=\"width:304px;max-width:304px\"><div class=\"tsingle\" style=\"margin:1px;width:302px;max-width:302px\"><div class=\"thumbimage\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Cross-serial_dependencies.png\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/ce/Cross-serial_dependencies.png/300px-Cross-serial_dependencies.png\" width=\"300\" height=\"115\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/ce/Cross-serial_dependencies.png/450px-Cross-serial_dependencies.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/ce/Cross-serial_dependencies.png/600px-Cross-serial_dependencies.png 2x\" data-file-width=\"1569\" data-file-height=\"603\" /></a></div><div class=\"thumbcaption\" style=\"clear:left\">A Swiss-German sentence containing cross-serial dependencies (shown as lines between the verbs and their objects). The English translation with its dependencies, which do not cross, is shown for comparison.</div></div><div class=\"tsingle\" style=\"margin:1px;width:302px;max-width:302px\"><div class=\"thumbimage\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Cross-serial_dependencies_2.png\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/83/Cross-serial_dependencies_2.png/300px-Cross-serial_dependencies_2.png\" width=\"300\" height=\"77\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/83/Cross-serial_dependencies_2.png/450px-Cross-serial_dependencies_2.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/83/Cross-serial_dependencies_2.png/600px-Cross-serial_dependencies_2.png 2x\" data-file-width=\"1262\" data-file-height=\"326\" /></a></div><div class=\"thumbcaption\" style=\"clear:left\">A more complicated example.</div></div></div></div>\n<p>As Swiss-German allows verbs and their arguments to be ordered cross-serially, we have the following example, taken from Shieber:<sup id=\"cite_ref-shieber1985_4-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-shieber1985-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<table cellpadding=\"5\">\n\n<tbody><tr>\n<td>...<i>mer</i></td>\n<td><i>em Hans</i></td>\n<td><i>es</i></td>\n<td><i>huus</i></td>\n<td><i>h\u00e4lfed</i></td>\n<td><i>aastriiche.</i>\n</td></tr>\n<tr>\n<td>...<i>we</i></td>\n<td><i>Hans</i> (<a href=\"/wiki/Dative_case\" title=\"Dative case\"><span class=\"smallcaps\" style=\"font-variant:small-caps;\"><b>dat</b></span></a>)</td>\n<td><i>the</i></td>\n<td><i>house</i> (<a href=\"/wiki/Accusative_case\" title=\"Accusative case\"><span class=\"smallcaps\" style=\"font-variant:small-caps;\"><b>acc</b></span></a>)</td>\n<td><i>help</i></td>\n<td><i>paint.</i>\n</td></tr></tbody></table>\n<p>That is, \"we help Hans paint the house.\"\n</p><p>Notice that the sequential noun phrases <i>em Hans</i> (<i>Hans</i>) and <i>es huus</i> (<i>the house</i>), and the sequential verbs <i>h\u00e4lfed</i> (<i>help</i>) and <i>aastriiche</i> (<i>paint</i>) both form two separate series of constituents. Notice also that the <a href=\"/wiki/Dative_case\" title=\"Dative case\">dative verb</a> <i>h\u00e4lfed</i> and the <a href=\"/wiki/Accusative_case\" title=\"Accusative case\">accusative verb</a> <i>aastriiche</i> take the dative <i>em Hans</i> and accusative <i>s huus</i> as their arguments, respectively.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Why_languages_containing_cross-serial_dependencies_are_non-context-free\">Why languages containing cross-serial dependencies are non-context-free</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Cross-serial_dependencies&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: Why languages containing cross-serial dependencies are non-context-free\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>In Swiss-German sentences, the number of verbs of a <a href=\"/wiki/Grammatical_case\" title=\"Grammatical case\">grammatical case</a> (dative or accusative) must match the number of objects of that case. Additionally, a sentence containing an arbitrary number of such objects is admissible (in principle). Hence, the following <a href=\"/wiki/Formal_language\" title=\"Formal language\">formal language</a> is grammatical:\n</p><p><span class=\"mwe-math-element\"><span class=\"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y\" style=\"display: none;\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"  alttext=\"{\\displaystyle L={\\text{De Jan}}{\\text{ s}}{\\ddot {\\mathrm {a} }}{\\text{it}}{\\text{ das}}{\\text{ mer}}{\\text{ (d'chind)}}{}^{m}{\\text{ (em}}{\\text{ Hans)}}{}^{n}{\\text{ s}}{\\text{ huus}}{\\text{ h}}{\\ddot {\\mathrm {a} }}{\\text{nd}}{\\text{ wele}}{\\text{ (laa)}}{}^{m}{\\text{ (h}}{\\ddot {\\mathrm {a} }}{\\text{lfe)}}{}^{n}{\\text{ aastriiche.}}}\">\n  <semantics>\n    <mrow class=\"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD\">\n      <mstyle displaystyle=\"true\" scriptlevel=\"0\">\n        <mi>L</mi>\n        <mo>=</mo>\n        <mrow class=\"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD\">\n          <mtext>De Jan</mtext>\n        </mrow>\n        <mrow class=\"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD\">\n          <mtext>&#xA0;s</mtext>\n        </mrow>\n        <mrow class=\"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD\">\n          <mrow class=\"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD\">\n            <mover>\n              <mrow class=\"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD\">\n                <mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi>\n              </mrow>\n              <mo>&#x00A8;<!-- \u00a8 --></mo>\n            </mover>\n          </mrow>\n        </mrow>\n        <mrow class=\"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD\">\n          <mtext>it</mtext>\n        </mrow>\n        <mrow class=\"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD\">\n          <mtext>&#xA0;das</mtext>\n        </mrow>\n        <mrow class=\"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD\">\n          <mtext>&#xA0;mer</mtext>\n        </mrow>\n        <mrow class=\"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD\">\n          <mtext>&#xA0;(d'chind)</mtext>\n        </mrow>\n        <msup>\n          <mrow class=\"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD\">\n\n          </mrow>\n          <mrow class=\"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD\">\n            <mi>m</mi>\n          </mrow>\n        </msup>\n        <mrow class=\"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD\">\n          <mtext>&#xA0;(em</mtext>\n        </mrow>\n        <mrow class=\"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD\">\n          <mtext>&#xA0;Hans)</mtext>\n        </mrow>\n        <msup>\n          <mrow class=\"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD\">\n\n          </mrow>\n          <mrow class=\"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD\">\n            <mi>n</mi>\n          </mrow>\n        </msup>\n        <mrow class=\"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD\">\n          <mtext>&#xA0;s</mtext>\n        </mrow>\n        <mrow class=\"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD\">\n          <mtext>&#xA0;huus</mtext>\n        </mrow>\n        <mrow class=\"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD\">\n          <mtext>&#xA0;h</mtext>\n        </mrow>\n        <mrow class=\"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD\">\n          <mrow class=\"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD\">\n            <mover>\n              <mrow class=\"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD\">\n                <mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi>\n              </mrow>\n              <mo>&#x00A8;<!-- \u00a8 --></mo>\n            </mover>\n          </mrow>\n        </mrow>\n        <mrow class=\"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD\">\n          <mtext>nd</mtext>\n        </mrow>\n        <mrow class=\"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD\">\n          <mtext>&#xA0;wele</mtext>\n        </mrow>\n        <mrow class=\"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD\">\n          <mtext>&#xA0;(laa)</mtext>\n        </mrow>\n        <msup>\n          <mrow class=\"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD\">\n\n          </mrow>\n          <mrow class=\"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD\">\n            <mi>m</mi>\n          </mrow>\n        </msup>\n        <mrow class=\"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD\">\n          <mtext>&#xA0;(h</mtext>\n        </mrow>\n        <mrow class=\"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD\">\n          <mrow class=\"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD\">\n            <mover>\n              <mrow class=\"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD\">\n                <mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi>\n              </mrow>\n              <mo>&#x00A8;<!-- \u00a8 --></mo>\n            </mover>\n          </mrow>\n        </mrow>\n        <mrow class=\"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD\">\n          <mtext>lfe)</mtext>\n        </mrow>\n        <msup>\n          <mrow class=\"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD\">\n\n          </mrow>\n          <mrow class=\"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD\">\n            <mi>n</mi>\n          </mrow>\n        </msup>\n        <mrow class=\"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD\">\n          <mtext>&#xA0;aastriiche.</mtext>\n        </mrow>\n      </mstyle>\n    </mrow>\n    <annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">{\\displaystyle L={\\text{De Jan}}{\\text{ s}}{\\ddot {\\mathrm {a} }}{\\text{it}}{\\text{ das}}{\\text{ mer}}{\\text{ (d'chind)}}{}^{m}{\\text{ (em}}{\\text{ Hans)}}{}^{n}{\\text{ s}}{\\text{ huus}}{\\text{ h}}{\\ddot {\\mathrm {a} }}{\\text{nd}}{\\text{ wele}}{\\text{ (laa)}}{}^{m}{\\text{ (h}}{\\ddot {\\mathrm {a} }}{\\text{lfe)}}{}^{n}{\\text{ aastriiche.}}}</annotation>\n  </semantics>\n</math></span><img src=\"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/render/svg/322291880f2ee71e61ebe444cb7881be864aa6e0\" class=\"mwe-math-fallback-image-inline\" aria-hidden=\"true\" style=\"vertical-align: -0.838ex; width:92.066ex; height:2.843ex;\" alt=\" L =\\text{De Jan} \\text{ s}\\ddot{\\mathrm{a}}\\text{it} \\text{ das} \\text{ mer} \\text{ (d&#039;chind)}{}^m \\text{ (em} \\text{ Hans)}{}^n \\text{ s} \\text{ huus} \\text{ h}\\ddot{\\mathrm{a}}\\text{nd} \\text{ wele} \\text{ (laa)}{}^m \\text{ (h}\\ddot{\\mathrm{a}}\\text{lfe)}{}^n \\text{ aastriiche.} \"/></span>\n</p><p>It can be seen that <span class=\"mwe-math-element\"><span class=\"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y\" style=\"display: none;\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"  alttext=\"{\\displaystyle L}\">\n  <semantics>\n    <mrow class=\"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD\">\n      <mstyle displaystyle=\"true\" scriptlevel=\"0\">\n        <mi>L</mi>\n      </mstyle>\n    </mrow>\n    <annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">{\\displaystyle L}</annotation>\n  </semantics>\n</math></span><img src=\"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/render/svg/103168b86f781fe6e9a4a87b8ea1cebe0ad4ede8\" class=\"mwe-math-fallback-image-inline\" aria-hidden=\"true\" style=\"vertical-align: -0.338ex; width:1.583ex; height:2.176ex;\" alt=\"L\"/></span> is of the form <span class=\"mwe-math-element\"><span class=\"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y\" style=\"display: none;\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"  alttext=\"{\\displaystyle xa^{m}b^{n}yc^{m}d^{n}z}\">\n  <semantics>\n    <mrow class=\"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD\">\n      <mstyle displaystyle=\"true\" scriptlevel=\"0\">\n        <mi>x</mi>\n        <msup>\n          <mi>a</mi>\n          <mrow class=\"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD\">\n            <mi>m</mi>\n          </mrow>\n        </msup>\n        <msup>\n          <mi>b</mi>\n          <mrow class=\"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD\">\n            <mi>n</mi>\n          </mrow>\n        </msup>\n        <mi>y</mi>\n        <msup>\n          <mi>c</mi>\n          <mrow class=\"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD\">\n            <mi>m</mi>\n          </mrow>\n        </msup>\n        <msup>\n          <mi>d</mi>\n          <mrow class=\"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD\">\n            <mi>n</mi>\n          </mrow>\n        </msup>\n        <mi>z</mi>\n      </mstyle>\n    </mrow>\n    <annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">{\\displaystyle xa^{m}b^{n}yc^{m}d^{n}z}</annotation>\n  </semantics>\n</math></span><img src=\"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/render/svg/9c9ae36627ad2c7e4225353d1a5c9bff375a29fa\" class=\"mwe-math-fallback-image-inline\" aria-hidden=\"true\" style=\"vertical-align: -0.671ex; width:13.813ex; height:2.676ex;\" alt=\"x a^m b^n y c^m d^n z\"/></span>. By taking another image<sup class=\"noprint Inline-Template\" style=\"margin-left:0.1em; white-space:nowrap;\">&#91;<i><a href=\"/wiki/Wikipedia:Please_clarify\" title=\"Wikipedia:Please clarify\"><span title=\"&quot;Image&quot; has not been previously used or defined (August 2016)\">clarification needed</span></a></i>&#93;</sup> to remove the <span class=\"mwe-math-element\"><span class=\"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y\" style=\"display: none;\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"  alttext=\"{\\displaystyle x}\">\n  <semantics>\n    <mrow class=\"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD\">\n      <mstyle displaystyle=\"true\" scriptlevel=\"0\">\n        <mi>x</mi>\n      </mstyle>\n    </mrow>\n    <annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">{\\displaystyle x}</annotation>\n  </semantics>\n</math></span><img src=\"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/render/svg/87f9e315fd7e2ba406057a97300593c4802b53e4\" class=\"mwe-math-fallback-image-inline\" aria-hidden=\"true\" style=\"vertical-align: -0.338ex; width:1.33ex; height:1.676ex;\" alt=\"x\"/></span>, <span class=\"mwe-math-element\"><span class=\"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y\" style=\"display: none;\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"  alttext=\"{\\displaystyle y}\">\n  <semantics>\n    <mrow class=\"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD\">\n      <mstyle displaystyle=\"true\" scriptlevel=\"0\">\n        <mi>y</mi>\n      </mstyle>\n    </mrow>\n    <annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">{\\displaystyle y}</annotation>\n  </semantics>\n</math></span><img src=\"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/render/svg/b8a6208ec717213d4317e666f1ae872e00620a0d\" class=\"mwe-math-fallback-image-inline\" aria-hidden=\"true\" style=\"vertical-align: -0.671ex; width:1.155ex; height:2.009ex;\" alt=\"y\"/></span> and <span class=\"mwe-math-element\"><span class=\"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y\" style=\"display: none;\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"  alttext=\"{\\displaystyle z}\">\n  <semantics>\n    <mrow class=\"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD\">\n      <mstyle displaystyle=\"true\" scriptlevel=\"0\">\n        <mi>z</mi>\n      </mstyle>\n    </mrow>\n    <annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">{\\displaystyle z}</annotation>\n  </semantics>\n</math></span><img src=\"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/render/svg/bf368e72c009decd9b6686ee84a375632e11de98\" class=\"mwe-math-fallback-image-inline\" aria-hidden=\"true\" style=\"vertical-align: -0.338ex; width:1.088ex; height:1.676ex;\" alt=\"z\"/></span>, the non-context-free<sup id=\"cite_ref-hopcroft2000_5-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-hopcroft2000-5\">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup><sup class=\"noprint Inline-Template\" style=\"margin-left:0.1em; white-space:nowrap;\">&#91;<i><a href=\"/wiki/Wikipedia:Please_clarify\" title=\"Wikipedia:Please clarify\"><span title=\"In formal language theory, a language is a set of sentences, whereas the swiss example is a signals sentence. An exponent n denotes n-fold repetition in the cited book, whereas e.g. &#39;em Hans em Hans&#39; is not valid Swiss. (February 2014)\">clarification needed</span></a></i>&#93;</sup> language <span class=\"mwe-math-element\"><span class=\"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y\" style=\"display: none;\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"  alttext=\"{\\displaystyle L'=a^{m}b^{n}c^{m}d^{n}}\">\n  <semantics>\n    <mrow class=\"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD\">\n      <mstyle displaystyle=\"true\" scriptlevel=\"0\">\n        <msup>\n          <mi>L</mi>\n          <mo>&#x2032;</mo>\n        </msup>\n        <mo>=</mo>\n        <msup>\n          <mi>a</mi>\n          <mrow class=\"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD\">\n            <mi>m</mi>\n          </mrow>\n        </msup>\n        <msup>\n          <mi>b</mi>\n          <mrow class=\"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD\">\n            <mi>n</mi>\n          </mrow>\n        </msup>\n        <msup>\n          <mi>c</mi>\n          <mrow class=\"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD\">\n            <mi>m</mi>\n          </mrow>\n        </msup>\n        <msup>\n          <mi>d</mi>\n          <mrow class=\"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD\">\n            <mi>n</mi>\n          </mrow>\n        </msup>\n      </mstyle>\n    </mrow>\n    <annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">{\\displaystyle L'=a^{m}b^{n}c^{m}d^{n}}</annotation>\n  </semantics>\n</math></span><img src=\"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/render/svg/5f4ac9052310c3eb0af38cf3385b90b748d539c7\" class=\"mwe-math-fallback-image-inline\" aria-hidden=\"true\" style=\"vertical-align: -0.338ex; width:15.605ex; height:2.509ex;\" alt=\"L&#039; = a^m b^n c^m d^n \"/></span> may be observed. All spoken languages which contain cross-serial dependencies also contain a language of a form similar to <span class=\"mwe-math-element\"><span class=\"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y\" style=\"display: none;\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"  alttext=\"{\\displaystyle L'}\">\n  <semantics>\n    <mrow class=\"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD\">\n      <mstyle displaystyle=\"true\" scriptlevel=\"0\">\n        <msup>\n          <mi>L</mi>\n          <mo>&#x2032;</mo>\n        </msup>\n      </mstyle>\n    </mrow>\n    <annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">{\\displaystyle L'}</annotation>\n  </semantics>\n</math></span><img src=\"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/render/svg/7a5bf7164faabe6b737c3d5269366b5e17f2ac7c\" class=\"mwe-math-fallback-image-inline\" aria-hidden=\"true\" style=\"vertical-align: -0.338ex; width:2.268ex; height:2.509ex;\" alt=\"L&#039;\"/></span>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-jurafsky2000_2-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-jurafsky2000-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Treatment\">Treatment</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Cross-serial_dependencies&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3\" title=\"Edit section: Treatment\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>Research in <a href=\"/wiki/Mildly_context-sensitive_language\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Mildly context-sensitive language\">mildly context-sensitive language</a> has attempted to identify a narrower and more computationally tractable subclass of <a href=\"/wiki/Context-sensitive_language\" title=\"Context-sensitive language\">context-sensitive languages</a> that can capture context sensitivity as found in natural languages. For example cross-serial dependencies can be expressed in <a href=\"/wiki/Linear_context-free_rewriting_system\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Linear context-free rewriting system\">linear context-free rewriting systems</a> (LCFRS); one can write a LCFRS grammar for {<i>a<sup>n</sup>b<sup>n</sup>c<sup>n</sup>d<sup>n</sup></i> | <i>n</i> \u2265 1} for example.<sup id=\"cite_ref-6\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-6\">&#91;6&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-7\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-7\">&#91;7&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-Kallmeyer2010_8-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Kallmeyer2010-8\">&#91;8&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Cross-serial_dependencies&amp;action=edit&amp;section=4\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-stabler2004-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-stabler2004_1-0\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite id=\"CITEREFStabler2004\" class=\"citation\">Stabler, Edward (2004), <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.linguistics.ucla.edu/people/stabler/Stabler04-Copying.pdf\">\"Varieties of crossing dependencies: structure dependence and mild context sensitivity\"</a> <span style=\"font-size:85%;\">(PDF)</span>, <i>Cognitive Science</i>, <b>28</b>: 699\u2013720, <a href=\"/wiki/Digital_object_identifier\" title=\"Digital object identifier\">doi</a>:<a rel=\"no